    ),
    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='# Disclosures on Common-Control Accounting, the xAI Merger, and the X Holdings Merger\n\n## 1. Common-Control Accounting Framework\n\nThe document discloses that both mergers were accounted for as **reorganizations of entities under common control**. The justification is that Elon Musk held a controlling financial interest in SpaceX, xAI, and X through his majority voting interest in each entity during all periods presented. This is a critical accounting election because it dictates the entire retrospective treatment.\n\nKey accounting consequences disclosed:\n\n- **Retrospective combination at historical carrying amounts** — The net assets of xAI and X are combined into SpaceX\'s financials at their historical carrying values for *all periods presented*, not at fair value at the acquisition date.\n- **No new goodwill or intangible assets recorded** — Unlike an arm\'s-length acquisition under ASC 805, no purchase price allocation occurs, meaning no goodwill or acquired intangibles appear on the balance sheet from these transactions.\n- **Elimination of all historical related-party transactions** — Any commercial dealings between SpaceX, xAI, and X during historical periods are eliminated in consolidation, removing what could have been material revenue or cost line items.\n- **Change in reporting entity** — The document explicitly states this presentation "constitutes a change in reporting entity," triggering retrospective application across all comparative periods.\n\n## 2. Merger Timeline and Structure\n\n| Transaction | Date | Acquirer | Target | Legal Form |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| X Merger | March 28, 2025 | xAI | X Holdings Corp. and X.AI Corp. | Share exchange |\n| xAI Merger | February 2, 2026 | SpaceX | X.AI Holdings Corp. (xAI) | Share exchange |\n\nSupporting context: X.AI Corp. began operations in March 2023, and Twitter was acquired by Musk in October 2022.\n\n## 3. How Historical Periods Are Recast\n\nThe recasting operates on two dimensions:\n\n### a. Income Statement and Balance Sheet Recasting\n- All historical periods presented (2023, 2024, 2025, and interim 2026) now include the **fully combined results** of SpaceX, xAI, and X as if they had always been a single entity.\n- Intercompany transactions between the three entities are eliminated for all periods.\n- The document states: *"The summary historical consolidated financial and operating data of SpaceX has been prepared to reflect the retrospective combination of the companies for all periods presented."*\n\n### b. Share Count and Equity Recasting\nHistorical share counts are adjusted using the following exchange ratios:\n\n| Security Converted | Conversion Ratio | Into |\n|---|---|---|\n| X Holdings common stock | 2.776 shares | xAI common stock (same class) |\n| X.AI Corp. common stock | 1.000 share | xAI common stock (same class) |\n| X.AI Corp. preferred stock | 1.000 share | xAI Redeemable Convertible Preferred Stock |\n| xAI common stock | 0.1433 shares | SpaceX common stock |\n| xAI warrants | 0.1433 shares | SpaceX Class A common stock (cashless) |\n\nAll share and per-share data is then further adjusted for the **five-for-one 2026 Stock Split** (effective May 4, 2026) on a retroactive basis.\n\n### c. Important Exception — xAI Redeemable Convertible Preferred Stock\nThe document discloses a **critical limitation on the retrospective recasting**: xAI\'s Redeemable Convertible Preferred Stock is *not* recast on an as-converted basis for periods prior to the xAI Merger date. Because it was legally outstanding as a separate equity class of a legally distinct predecessor entity, its conversion into SpaceX common stock is recognized **only prospectively** as of February 2, 2026. Historical balance sheets continue to show it as outstanding xAI preferred stock.\n\n## 4. Limitations for Identifying Standalone SpaceX Revenue\n\nThe retrospective combination creates several significant limitations for any reader attempting to isolate standalone SpaceX revenue:\n\n### a. No Segregation of Pre-Merger Results\nBecause the financials are recast for *all periods presented*, there is no line-item disclosure separating SpaceX-only revenue from xAI-only or X-only revenue in the historical periods. The combined entity\'s revenue is presented as a single consolidated figure for 2023, 2024, and 2025 — even though xAI was not legally acquired by SpaceX until February 2026 and X was not acquired by xAI until March 2025.\n\n### b. Elimination of Intercompany Revenue\nThe document states that *"all historical related party transactions between the entities have been eliminated in consolidation."* This means any revenue that SpaceX may have recognized from transactions with xAI or X (or vice versa) during 2023–2025 is removed from the consolidated totals. A reader cannot determine from the face of the financial statements how much intercompany revenue existed or what its nature was.\n\n### c. No Separate Financial Statements Provided\nThe document explicitly justifies the omission of standalone financials: *"As the consolidated financial statements already reflect the reorganization of entities under common control for all periods presented, separate financial statements of xAI and X are not provided."* This eliminates the primary mechanism a reader would normally use to reconstruct standalone results.\n\n### d. Management\'s Own Caution\nThe document includes an explicit disclaimer that the summary historical data is *"not indicative of the results to be expected for any future period, and the results for any interim period are not necessarily indicative of the results to be expected for the full fiscal period."* This suggests that the combined historical figures may not even be useful as a run-rate proxy, because the entities operated independently during those periods.\n\n### e. Change in Reporting Entity Complicates Trend Analysis\nBecause the presentation constitutes a change in reporting entity, year-over-year comparisons within the recast financials reflect the combined entity throughout, making it impossible to assess SpaceX\'s organic growth trajectory, margin profile, or capital efficiency on a standalone basis from the consolidated disclosures alone.\n\n### f. Related-Party Commercial Relationships Are Only Partially Disclosed\nWhile the document does disclose certain related-party transaction amounts with Tesla (e.g., xAI obtained $191 million in goods/services from Tesla in 2024, $506 million in 2025), the intercompany economics *among* SpaceX, xAI, and X prior to consolidation are not separately quantified in the preamble sections provided. This means a reader cannot reconstruct what portion of any entity\'s historical revenue was derived from the other two entities now in the consolidated group.\n\n## Summary\n\nThe disclosure framework presents a fully combined SpaceX-xAI-X entity for all historical periods, with no goodwill, no standalone financials, and no visible intercompany revenue. While this is the correct GAAP treatment for common-control combinations, it means that **standalone SpaceX revenue for any historical period cannot be directly identified from the consolidated financial statements as presented**. A reader would need segment-level disclosures (if provided elsewhere in the prospectus) or non-GAAP supplemental information to attempt any such reconstruction, and even then, the elimination of intercompany transactions would limit precision.',
