        output='## Decomposition of Recast Consolidated FY2025 Revenue and Implied Standalone SpaceX Valuation Multiple\n\n### 1. Consolidated FY2025 Revenue Disclosed in the S-1\n\nThe SpaceX S-1 (filed May 20, 2026) reports total consolidated revenue of **$18,674 million (~$18.7 billion)** for fiscal year 2025, disaggregated by reportable segment as follows:\n\n| Segment | FY2025 Revenue ($M) | Composition |\n|---|---|---|\n| Space | $4,086 | SpaceX launch services & development |\n| Connectivity | $11,387 | Starlink (consumer + enterprise/government) |\n| AI | $3,201 | xAI + X Holdings (Grok, X platform, AI compute) |\n| **Total** | **$18,674** | Recast consolidated entity |\n\nThe S-1 explicitly defines the AI segment as including "our AI business, which we acquired in connection with our acquisition of xAI in February 2026, and includes our AI compute, Grok, and X." This confirms that the AI segment corresponds to the combined xAI + X Holdings operations.\n\n### 2. Implied Revenue Contribution of xAI and X Holdings\n\nReuters reported on January 30, 2026 (pre-S-1) that SpaceX generated approximately **$15–16 billion in revenue in 2025** on a standalone pre-merger basis. Using the S-1\'s recast consolidated total of $18,674 million and the Reuters standalone estimate:\n\n| Reuters Standalone Estimate | Implied xAI + X Contribution |\n|---|---|\n| $15.0B (low) | $18.674B − $15.0B = **$3.674B** |\n| $15.5B (midpoint) | $18.674B − $15.5B = **$3.174B** |\n| $16.0B (high) | $18.674B − $16.0B = **$2.674B** |\n\n**Implied xAI + X Holdings revenue contribution: approximately $2.7B–$3.7B, with a midpoint of ~$3.2B.**\n\nThis estimate is remarkably consistent with the S-1\'s AI segment revenue of **$3,201 million (~$3.2B)**, providing strong corroboration. Conversely, the Space + Connectivity segments combined total **$15,473 million (~$15.5B)**, which falls squarely within the Reuters standalone SpaceX range of $15–16B. This internal consistency confirms that:\n- The Space and Connectivity segments effectively represent the standalone SpaceX business (~82.9% of consolidated revenue)\n- The AI segment represents the xAI + X Holdings contribution (~17.1% of consolidated revenue)\n\n### 3. Implied Valuation Multiple on Standalone SpaceX (Pre-xAI Merger)\n\nIn December 2025—before the xAI merger closed on February 2, 2026—SpaceX conducted a secondary share sale (tender offer) that valued the company at approximately **$800 billion**. This was the last secondary market valuation reflecting the standalone SpaceX business before the xAI combination.\n\nUsing the Reuters standalone revenue estimate of $15–16B:\n\n| Standalone Revenue | Implied EV/Revenue Multiple |\n|---|---|\n| $15.0B | $800B / $15.0B = **53.3x** |\n| $15.5B (midpoint) | $800B / $15.5B = **51.6x** |\n| $16.0B | $800B / $16.0B = **50.0x** |\n\n**Implied standalone SpaceX EV/Revenue multiple: approximately 50x–53x (midpoint ~51.6x).**\n\nThis is an extraordinarily rich revenue multiple—well above typical aerospace/defense multiples (typically 2–5x revenue) and even above most high-growth software/AI comparables. The multiple implies that secondary market investors were pricing in:\n- Massive future growth from Starlink expansion (consumer + enterprise/government + direct-to-cell)\n- Continued dominance of the global launch market\n- Future commercialization of Starship\n- Exceptional margin profile (Reuters separately reported ~$8B EBITDA on $15–16B revenue, implying ~50% EBITDA margins)\n- A scarcity premium as the only scaled, pure-play space infrastructure company\n\nIn effect, secondary market investors were valuing standalone SpaceX at a multiple typically reserved for the highest-growth, highest-margin software franchises, despite SpaceX\'s revenue being derived primarily from capital-intensive launch and satellite connectivity hardware/services.\n\n### 4. Accounting Limitation Preventing a Clean Standalone SpaceX Revenue Figure\n\nThe S-1 cannot provide a clean standalone SpaceX revenue figure for FY2025 (or any historical period) due to **common-control accounting under ASC 805-50**. The specific limitations are:\n\n**(a) Retrospective combination at historical carrying amounts.** Because Elon Musk held a controlling financial interest in SpaceX, xAI, and X during all periods presented, both mergers were accounted for as reorganizations of entities under common control. The net assets of xAI and X are combined into SpaceX\'s financials at their historical carrying values for **all periods presented** (2023, 2024, 2025, and interim 2026)—not at fair value as of the acquisition date. This constitutes a "change in reporting entity" requiring retrospective application.\n\n**(b) No standalone financial statements provided.** The S-1 explicitly states: *"As the consolidated financial statements already reflect the reorganization of entities under common control for all periods presented, separate financial statements of xAI and X are not provided."* This eliminates the primary mechanism a reader would normally use to reconstruct standalone results.\n\n**(c) Elimination of all intercompany transactions.** The filing states that *"all historical related party transactions between the entities have been eliminated in consolidation."* Any revenue SpaceX may have recognized from transactions with xAI or X (or vice versa) during 2023–2025 is removed from the consolidated totals, and the filing does not separately quantify the magnitude or nature of these intercompany revenues. A reader therefore cannot determine from the face of the financial statements how much intercompany revenue existed.\n\n**(d) No purchase price allocation or goodwill.** Unlike an arm\'s-length acquisition under ASC 805, no purchase price allocation occurs, meaning no goodwill or acquired intangibles appear on the balance sheet from these transactions. This further obscures the economic substance of what was acquired.\n\n**(e) Segment disclosure is a proxy, not a legal-entity standalone.** While the segment breakdown (Space + Connectivity vs. AI) provides a useful proxy for isolating SpaceX-only revenue (~$15.5B) from xAI + X revenue (~$3.2B), this is a management-defined operating segment disaggregation, not a legal-entity-level standalone financial statement. It still reflects intercompany eliminations that may have affected the historical revenue figures of each entity, and the segment structure was only realigned effective Q1 2026 with prior periods conformed.\n\n**Bottom line:** The S-1\'s recast consolidated financials present a fully combined SpaceX-xAI-X entity for all historical periods, making it impossible to directly identify standalone SpaceX revenue from the consolidated disclosures. The Reuters pre-filing estimate (~$15–16B) and the S-1\'s segment disaggregation (Space + Connectivity = ~$15.5B) converge to confirm that xAI and X Holdings contributed approximately $3.2B to the recast consolidated FY2025 revenue of $18.7B. The implied ~50–53x EV/Revenue multiple on standalone SpaceX at the December 2025 $800B secondary market valuation reflects an exceptionally rich assessment of SpaceX\'s growth and margin trajectory by pre-IPO investors.\n\n---\n\n{\n  "sources": [\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm",\n      "name": "SpaceX S-1 Registration Statement (filed May 20, 2026) — Consolidated Statements of Operations, Segment Disclosures, and Common-Control Accounting Footnotes"\n    },\n    {\n      "url": "https://reuters.com/business/finance/spacex-generated-about-8-billion-profit-last-year-ahead-ipo-sources-say-2026-01-30",\n      "name": "Reuters — \'Exclusive: SpaceX generated about $8 billion in profit last year ahead of IPO, sources say\' (January 30, 2026)"\n    },\n    {\n      "url": "https://news.satnews.com/2025/12/06/spacex-targets-800-billion-valuation-in-secondary-sale-eyes-2026-ipo",\n      "name": "SatNews — \'SpaceX Targets $800 Billion Valuation in Secondary Sale, Eyes 2026 IPO\' (December 6, 2025, citing WSJ)"\n    },\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.straitstimes.com/business/companies-markets/spacex-generated-about-10-billion-in-profit-last-year-ahead-of-ipo-sources-say",\n      "name": "The Straits Times — \'SpaceX generated about $10 billion in profit last year ahead of IPO, sources say\' (January 31, 2026, citing Reuters)"\n    }\n  ]\n}',
